README.txt - Student Management System (HW2)

DESCRIPTION OF CLASSES

Student.java - represents a student with ID, name, email, GPA, major, and year.
  implements Comparable to allow sorting by GPA.

Course.java - represents a course with code, name, credits, instructor, max enrollment,
  and a list of prerequisite course codes.

Enrollment.java - represents a students enrollment in a course for a semester.
  tracks the grade and has helpers like getGradePoints() and isPassing().

StudentManager.java - manages an ArrayList of Students. can add, remove, find,
  and filter students by major, year, or GPA. calculates average GPA.

CourseManager.java - manages an ArrayList of Courses. can add, find, and list courses.
  getAvailableCourses checks prerequisites and current enrollments.

EnrollmentManager.java - manages an ArrayList of Enrollments. handles enrolling,
  dropping, assigning grades, and calculating GPA from enrollment records.

ReportGenerator.java - generates reports for students, courses, majors, and honor roll.

ArrayListUtils.java - generic utility methods like swap, findMax, filter, reverse, merge.
  also has bounded generic methods for Numbers and wildcard demonstrations.

GenericPredicate.java - simple generic interface with a test method for filtering.

GenericList.java - generic wrapper around ArrayList. has add, get, remove, size,
  isEmpty, clear, contains, getAll, addAll, addAllFrom, sort, and findMax.

GenericStack.java - generic stack (LIFO) using ArrayList. push, pop, peek.

GenericQueue.java - generic queue (FIFO) using ArrayList. enqueue, dequeue, peek.

Pair.java - generic class with two type parameters K and V. has getters setters
  equals hashCode and toString.

ArrayListOperationsDemo.java - demonstrates array to ArrayList conversion,
  subList operations, sorting with Comparator, and searching.

ArrayListVsArrayDemo.java - compares arrays vs ArrayLists showing limitations
  of arrays and measuring performance.

StudentManagementSystemMain.java - main application with sample data, generics
  demo, and interactive menu system.


HOW TO COMPILE AND RUN

open in IntelliJ with all files in an HW2 folder inside src.
right click StudentManagementSystemMain.java and hit Run.
for the demos right click ArrayListOperationsDemo or ArrayListVsArrayDemo and Run.


DESIGN DECISIONS

- Student implements Comparable comparing by GPA descending so sorting puts highest first.
- made a GenericPredicate interface instead of using java.util.function.Predicate
  to keep it simple and show how interfaces work with generics.
- enrollment IDs are auto generated with a counter (E001, E002, etc).
- used String.format for GPA output to keep it to 2 decimal places.
- GenericList sort and findMax use try catch since we cant enforce Comparable
  at the class level without changing the type parameter.


CHALLENGES

- understanding that subList returns a view not a copy.
- binarySearch needs the list sorted by the same ordering as compareTo.
- bounded generics syntax like <T extends Number & Comparable<T>> was tricky at first.
- wildcards (? extends, ? super, ?) are confusing but PECS helps:
  Producer Extends, Consumer Super.


WHAT I LEARNED

- ArrayLists handle resizing automatically unlike arrays where you manually
  create a new array and copy everything.
- generics give type safety at compile time so you cant accidentally put
  the wrong type in a collection.
- <T extends Comparable<T>> lets you write methods that work with any
  comparable type making code reusable.
- wildcards make methods even more flexible. extends for reading,
  super for writing, ? for just iterating.


ARRAYLIST VS ARRAY

arrays are faster for direct access and use less memory but they are fixed size.
ArrayLists grow dynamically and have useful methods like add remove and contains
but have slightly more overhead. for most cases where size isnt known ahead
of time ArrayLists are the better choice. arrays are better when you know
the exact size and need performance with primitives.